		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Yotsuya Kaidan</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kuniyoshi_oiwa.jpg" class="image" title="Utagawa Kuniyoshi's portrait of Oiwa."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Kuniyoshi_oiwa.jpg/250px-Kuniyoshi_oiwa.jpg" width="250" height="367" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kuniyoshi_oiwa.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Utagawa_Kuniyoshi" title="Utagawa Kuniyoshi">Utagawa Kuniyoshi</a>'s portrait of Oiwa.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><i><b>Yotsuya Kaidan</b></i> (四谷怪談), the story of Oiwa and Tamiya Iemon,<span class="reference plainlinksneverexpand" id="ref_iemon"><sup><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yotsuya_Kaidan#endnote_iemon" class="external autonumber" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yotsuya_Kaidan#endnote_iemon" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></sup></span> is a tale of betrayal, murder and <a href="/wiki/Onryou" title="Onryou" class="mw-redirect">ghostly revenge</a>. Arguably the most famous <a href="/wiki/Kaidan" title="Kaidan">Japanese ghost story</a> of all time, it has been adapted for film over 30 times, and continues to be an influence on <a href="/wiki/J-horror" title="J-horror" class="mw-redirect">Japanese horror</a> today.</p>
<p>Written in 1825 by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tsuruya_Nanboku_IV&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tsuruya Nanboku IV (page does not exist)">Tsuruya Nanboku IV</a> as a <a href="/wiki/Kabuki" title="Kabuki">kabuki</a> play, the original title was <i>Tōkaidō Yotsuya Kaidan</i> (東海道四谷怪談).<sup id="cite_ref-Pacifica_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pacifica-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> It is now generally shortened, and loosely translates as <i>Ghost Story of Yotsuya.</i><span class="reference plainlinksneverexpand" id="ref_yotsuya"><sup><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yotsuya_Kaidan#endnote_yotsuya" class="external autonumber" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yotsuya_Kaidan#endnote_yotsuya" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></sup></span></p>
